    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-10-05T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-10-05T11:00:00-05:00" n="6"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d6">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">824.512/54: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Bolivia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Feely</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Paz</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-10-05T12:00:00-04:00"
                            >October 5, 1932—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received October 5—11:35
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>93. Department’s telegram No. 36, September 22, 5 p.m. The law was promulgated on
                    September 30th substantially as reported in my <pb facs="0091" n="3"
                        xml:id="pg_3"/> despatch 433 of September 14th,<note n="3" xml:id="d6fn3"
                        >Not printed.</note> enclosure number 1, the amount of the tax under
                    sections (<hi rend="italic">e</hi>) and (<hi rend="italic">f</hi>) of article 1
                    being definitely fixed at ⅕ of 1 percent per annum for 5 years.</p>
                <p>The British Chargé d’Affaires is today officially informing the Bolivian
                    Government that the British Government presumes British individuals and
                    corporations will be exempt from the provisions of the law under the terms of
                    article 9 of the British-Bolivian treaty.<note n="4" xml:id="d6fn4">Treaty of
                        August 1, 1911, <hi rend="italic">British and Foreign State Papers</hi>,
                        vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">civ</hi>, p. 132.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I am of the opinion that under the principle of equality of treatment, American
                    corporations and individuals should enjoy the same exemptions that may be
                    granted to other nationals.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Feely</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
